{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536005"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:02:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:02:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15563"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15563"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.11,0.13,0.66,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8254"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96425"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8254"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"44"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"3572"},{"type":"tags","id":"5788"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19947"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32644"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96425","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96425"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man has a medical emergency team (MET) call on the orthopaedic ward due to nursing concern for reduced consciousness. He is one day post right knee reconstruction following a motor vehicle accident. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears drowsy. His pulse rate is 58/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 10/min, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His Glasgow Coma Scale is 12 (Eyes 3, Verbal 4, Motor 5). His pupils are pinpoint. His right knee is wrapped in post-operative dressings with noted oedema and erythema. There are no signs of compartment syndrome. Blood tests reveal white cell count 14.5 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0) and C-reactive protein 116 mg/L (\u0026lt;5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Flumazenil","Urgent surgical review","Blood cultures","Naloxone","Computed tomography brain scan"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of opioid toxicity including reduced consciousness, respiratory depression, pinpoint pupils, and bradycardia. The timing and context (post-operative pain management) make iatrogenic opioid overdose the most likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaloxone\u003C/strong\u003E is the appropriate first-line treatment for suspected opioid overdose. It should be administered immediately when opioid toxicity is suspected, particularly in the presence of respiratory depression. The initial dose is typically 0.2-0.4mg intravenously, which can be repeated if necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography brain scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for unexplained reduced consciousness, but the clinical features here are classic for opioid toxicity and it is reasonable to trial immediate treatment rather than investigation. If there is ongoing alteration in conscious state despite adequate naloxone therapy a CT brain should be requested.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlumazenil\u003C/strong\u003E is the antidote for benzodiazepine overdose. While benzodiazepines can cause reduced consciousness, the pinpoint pupils and respiratory depression are more consistent with opioid toxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if sepsis was suspected. While this patient has elevated inflammatory markers, these are expected following recent surgery and do not explain the acute onset of reduced consciousness with pinpoint pupils.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent surgical review\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were concerns about surgical complications such as compartment syndrome or septic arthritis. However, the examination findings of the knee are consistent with recent operation without overt complications, and the clinical features are consistent with opioid toxicity requiring immediate medical management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Naloxone is the first-line treatment for suspected opioid overdose with respiratory depression.","Post-operative opioid overdose commonly presents with reduced consciousness and respiratory depression.","Elevated inflammatory markers are expected post-operatively and should not distract from recognising opioid toxicity."],"references":["Britch SC, Walsh SL. Treatment of opioid overdose: current approaches and recent advances. Psychopharmacology. 2022 Jul;239(7):2063-81. Available at; https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s00213-022-06125-5"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15563"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T13:14:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T13:17:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8254"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96425"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"ta